[{"id":"VR188327","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a rectangular circuit diagram with a battery, a resistor, and a capacitor. Beginning on the left vertical side and moving clockwise, the left vertical side has a battery labeled V. The top horizontal side has a 30 ohm resistor, the right vertical side has a capacitor labeled C, and the bottom horizontal branch is just a wire.\" height=\"137\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR188327.g03.png\" width=\"240\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A parallel-plate capacitor is connected in series with a battery and a <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"30 ohm\"><math alttext=\"30 ohm\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>30</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> resistor, as shown above. The capacitor consists of two circular metal plates with radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.0 centimeter\"><math alttext=\"1.0 centimeter\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>1.0</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>cm</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> that are separated only by a circular piece of paper with the same radius as the plates. When the capacitor is fully charged, each plate has an excess charge of magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"9.0 times 10 to the negative 11 power, coulomb\"><math alttext=\"9.0 times 10 to the negative 11 power, coulomb\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>9.0</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>11</mn></mrow></msup><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.3em\"></mspace><mtext>C</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> . The capacitor is replaced by a new capacitor made from two circular metal plates 